<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-034-580  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 034 580.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Jan 8 1990 n252 p22(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Software productivity: the next CASE. (next wave of computer-aidedsoftware engineering tools)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Soat, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The CASE market is expected to balloon from $1.4 billion in 1989to more than $4 billion in 1993.andP;  Despite CASE's drawbacks, itsproductivity gains are too great to be ignored by informationsystems managers.andP;  Many purchased CASE packages remain unusedbecause of user's misperceptions of the technology.andP;  CASE requiresa substantial investment in money, manpower and time.andP;  The culturechange associated with CASE adoption is often more difficult thanthe technological change, in part because of programmers'resistance to the technology.andP;  There are two basic types of CASEtools: those that automate front-end analysis and design, andthose that automate back-end code generation and implementation.andO;As the second wave of CASE tools come out, use is expected toskyrocket, especially since IBM has joined the fray with AD/Cycle.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer-Aided Software EngineeringForecastingMarket AnalysisResistance to ChangeCost of Programming.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Estimated growth of CASE market. (graph)Productivity impact of CASE tools during first 12 months of use.andO;(graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>